            // THEORY & CORE KNOWLEDGE (12 questions)
            {text:"Which statement correctly defines the mole concept?",options:["A mole is the amount of substance containing 6.022×10²³ entities, equal to the number of atoms in 12 g C-12","A mole is the mass of a substance in grams","A mole equals the molecular mass of any substance","A mole is 22.4 L of any gas at STP"],correct:0},
            {text:"What is the key difference between empirical and molecular formulas?",options:["Empirical formula shows simplest whole number ratio; molecular formula shows actual number of atoms in a molecule","Empirical formula is for ionic compounds; molecular formula is for covalent compounds","Empirical formula includes charge; molecular formula doesn't","Empirical formula is always larger than molecular formula"],correct:0},
            {text:"According to the Law of Conservation of Mass, which statement is correct?",options:["In a chemical reaction, total mass of reactants equals total mass of products","Mass is created during exothermic reactions","Mass is lost in endothermic reactions","Only moles are conserved, not mass"],correct:0},
            {text:"What does Avogadro's Law state?",options:["Equal volumes of gases at the same temperature and pressure contain equal numbers of molecules","Equal masses of gases contain equal molecules","All gases have the same molar volume at any condition","The volume of a gas is directly proportional to its mass"],correct:0},
            {text:"Which rule correctly describes oxidation number assignment?",options:["The oxidation number of oxygen in compounds is usually -2, except in peroxides (-1) and OF₂ (+2)","Oxygen always has oxidation number -2 in all compounds","The oxidation number of oxygen in O₂ is -2","Oxygen in peroxides has oxidation number -2"],correct:0},
            {text:"What defines a limiting reactant?",options:["The reactant that is completely consumed first and limits the amount of product formed","The reactant present in the smallest mass","The reactant with the smallest coefficient","The reactant that is most expensive"],correct:0},
            {text:"Which correctly defines percentage yield?",options:["(Actual yield / Theoretical yield) × 100%","(Theoretical yield / Actual yield) × 100%","(Limiting reactant / Excess reactant) × 100%","(Product mass / Reactant mass) × 100%"],correct:0},
            {text:"What is the correct definition of oxidation?",options:["Loss of electrons or increase in oxidation number","Gain of electrons","Addition of oxygen only","Removal of hydrogen only"],correct:0},
            {text:"What distinguishes a chemical change from a physical change?",options:["Chemical change forms new substances with different properties; physical change doesn't alter chemical composition","Chemical change is always irreversible; physical change is reversible","Chemical change involves color change only","Chemical change requires heat; physical change doesn't"],correct:0},
            {text:"What is the molar volume of any gas at STP?",options:["22.4 L/mol","1 L/mol","24.5 L/mol","Depends on the gas"],correct:0},
            {text:"Which best defines stoichiometry?",options:["The quantitative study of reactants and products in chemical reactions based on balanced equations","The study of chemical bonding","The measurement of reaction rates","The study of energy changes in reactions"],correct:0},
            {text:"What is the difference between molecular mass and molar mass?",options:["Molecular mass is in amu; molar mass is in g/mol (numerically equal for a given substance)","Molecular mass is always larger","Molar mass includes Avogadro's number","They are measured differently and have different values"],correct:0},
            // ACTIVITIES, EXPERIMENTS & REAL-LIFE APPLICATIONS (8 questions)
            {text:"When iron and sulfur are heated together in a laboratory, if the product is attracted to a magnet, what does this indicate about the reaction?",options:["The reaction was incomplete; unreacted iron remains","The product is magnetic iron sulfide","Iron cannot react with sulfur","The magnet contaminated the sample"],correct:0},
            {text:"In a decomposition experiment where lime water turns milky due to CO₂ produced, if you blow air through lime water, it also turns milky. What does this indicate?",options:["Exhaled air contains CO₂ from cellular respiration","Lime water reacts with nitrogen in air","Moisture in breath causes the change","Oxygen reacts with lime water"],correct:0},
            {text:"During the preparation of 'Shiro' powder from chickpeas, why is the final mass of Shiro less than the starting mass of chickpeas?",options:["Water evaporation, hull removal, and handling losses reduce mass","Chickpeas expand during processing","Mass is converted to energy","The scale was inaccurate"],correct:0},
            {text:"In a laboratory investigation where copper deposits on an iron rod immersed in copper sulfate solution, if the iron rod is removed before all CuSO₄ reacts, what would happen to the blue color?",options:["The blue color would remain because unreacted Cu²⁺ ions are still in solution","The solution would become colorless immediately","The solution would turn green","The copper would re-dissolve"],correct:0},
            {text:"When mixing two clear solutions produces a white precipitate, what laboratory technique would you use to separate this precipitate from the solution?",options:["Filtration","Distillation","Chromatography","Evaporation"],correct:0},
            {text:"When wood burns, the ash weighs much less than the original wood. If the reaction occurs in a closed container and you weigh the container before and after burning, what would you observe?",options:["Total mass remains constant (gases like CO₂ and H₂O are trapped inside)","Mass decreases because energy is released","Mass increases due to oxygen consumption","Mass cannot be measured in a closed system"],correct:0},
            {text:"In the fermentation of 'teff' to make injera, which compounds are the main products of fermentation?",options:["Ethanol and carbon dioxide","Glucose and water","Oxygen and lactic acid","Starch and protein"],correct:0},
            {text:"If you want to test whether a gas produced in a reaction is CO₂, which reagent would you use and what observation confirms its presence?",options:["Lime water; it turns milky/cloudy when CO₂ passes through","Litmus paper; turns red","Silver nitrate; white precipitate forms","Magnesium ribbon; burns brightly"],correct:0},
            {text:"When iron filings and sulfur powder are heated together in a laboratory, the reaction glows and continues even after removing the heat source. Which statement BEST explains this observation?",options:["The reaction is endothermic and absorbs heat from surroundings","The reaction is exothermic and releases enough heat to sustain itself","Sulfur has a low melting point that keeps the mixture hot","Iron catalyzes the decomposition of sulfur"],correct:1}
